GO analysis with clusters

#' breakStrings
#'
#' breaks a string of words (or vector thereof) into two lines
#'
#' @param x a character vector
#' @param minSizeForBreak the minimum number of characters to break on two lines (default 20)
#' @param lb the line break character (default "\n")
#'
#' @return a character vector of length=length(x)
#'
#' @export
breakStrings <- function(x, minSizeForBreak=20, lb="\n"){
   sapply(x,minSizeForBreak=minSizeForBreak,lb=lb,FUN=function(x,minSizeForBreak,lb){
      if(nchar(x)<=minSizeForBreak) return(x)
      g <- gregexpr(" ", x)[[1]]
      if(length(g)==0) return(x)
      if(length(g)==1 & all(g==-1)) return(x)
      mid <- nchar(x)/2
      mid <- g[order(abs(g-mid))[1]]
      substr(x, mid, mid) <- lb
      return(x)
   })
}

There we conducted our GO-analysis using the same clusters that had before been plotted in the heatmaps that investigated gene enrichment in the previous document.

The functions that were found for the different clusters can be seen in the plots above.

For example, GO-analysis on MR cluster 6 reveals important functions in neurogenesis and neuron differentiation, which are known to be inhibited during stress (Briones & Gould, 2019).

Compared to the previous GO analysis, that was performed without any cluster, with this one we were able to extrapolate some functions that are highly relevant in our context, but that did not seem important previously, probably because the set of regions that we are analysing globally might not be necessarily super specific for those functions. In the genome there are a huge number of genes, and specific functions are represented by a very low percentage of these. By grouping regions based on their similarity, and analysing those groups, those functions can emerge. The findings of the paper, that were confirmed by the previous GO analysis, might be correct, but these biological processes might not be the most relevant in a context of stress, or just before the start of the active phase, when glucocorticoids are usually released.
